<br>
Those naggy gloves are a great resist item.  Therefore all melee should get a shot at it.  That's the only part I'd really disgree with Bish on.<br>
<br>
Here's my 2cps on the hot topics some people have brought up:<br>
<br>
White scale--if someone isn't there at the raid to loot it for their epic that's just tough.  Just because it's rare doesn't mean a bard that wasn't even there should get it.<br>
<br>
--exception: Raid leader decides to reserve it as their item of choice.  Then it's up to the raid leader to give it to a bard in his guild, or a friend, etc.<br>
<br>
Haste items--no bards, sorry.  Two reasons already stated: 1) Bards already have many class specific and epic-related items they can roll on.  2) Bards get self haste song and in the high level game typically operate as buff and mez, not as melee.<br>
<br>
Raid leader reserving one item.  This is fine.  Organizing and leading a raid can be a pain.  This is especially true for raids leaders who repeatedly organize dragons raids to hopefully get themselves an epic-related item. <br>
<br>
One topic not discussed is a level minimum on these dragon raids.  I would say level 47 should be the minimum for Vox and Naggy raids.   Characters lower than that do not contribute enough to a raid to make a difference because they will not resist enough of the dragon fear and cold or fire dragon breath.<br>
<br>
Overall, the raid leader should state the loot rules just prior to the raid.  Latecomers are responsible for finding out the rules.  Don't refer people to some website for loot rules, that's just ridiculous.<br>
<br>
